culture","webTitle":"Culture","type":"keyword","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/culture/culture","sectionName":"Culture","references":[]},{"id":"books/fiction","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Fiction","type":"keyword","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/fiction","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books/fiction","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"culture/awards-and-prizes","sectionId":"culture","webTitle":"Awards and prizes","type":"keyword","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/culture/awards-and-prizes","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/culture/awards-and-prizes","sectionName":"Culture","references":[]},{"id":"books/neilgaiman","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Neil Gaiman","type":"keyword","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/neilgaiman","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books/neilgaiman","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"tone/news","webTitle":"News","type":"tone","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/tone/news","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/tone/news","references":[]},{"id":"tracking/commissioningdesk/uk-culture","webTitle":"UK Culture","type":"tracking","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/tracking/commissioningdesk/uk-culture","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/tracking/commissioningdesk/uk-culture","references":[]},{"id":"profile/alisonflood","webTitle":"Alison Flood","type":"contributor","bio":"<p>Alison Flood is a writer on guardian.co.uk/books and former news editor of the Bookseller</p>","bylineImageUrl":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/3/14/1300117336779/Alison.jpg","firstName":"","lastName":"flood","r2ContributorId":"27440","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/profile/alisonflood","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/profile/alisonflood","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-06-07T11:55:56Z","webTitle":"Andrea Wulf on a scientific adventurer 'chased by 10,000 pigs'","sectionId":"books","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"false"},"id":"books/2016/jun/07/andrea-wulf-a-journey-through-thousands-of-books-and-spectacular-landscapes","fields":{"commentable":"true","byline":"Andrea Wulf","headline":"Andrea Wulf on a scientific adventurer 'chased by 10,000 pigs'","trailText":"The author explains how her Costa-winning study of Alexander von Humboldt took her from libraries to mountaintops in South America","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>Part of me is blissfully happy when I’m locked up in dusty archives and wonderful libraries for weeks on end. I love falling into the words and worlds of “my” protagonists, immersing myself into their lives and thoughts. I become a hermit and disappear for while, but there always comes a point when my restlessness takes over and I have to get out, I need to see and feel the “real” world.</p> <p>So researching and writing a book about an intrepid explorer who likened his own adventurous drive to being chased by “10,000 pigs” was the perfect combination. Writing about Alexander von Humboldt in The Invention of Nature was a journey through thousands of letters and books, but also through spectacular landscapes.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/nov/13/the-invention-of-nature-the-adventures-of-alexander-von-humboldt-andrea-wulf-review\">The Invention of Nature: The Adventures of Alexander von Humboldt, the Lost Hero of Science by Andrea Wulf – review</a> </p> </aside>  <p>Humboldt was the most famous scientist of his age and a daring adventurer. In 1799, he went on a five-year exploration of Latin America, returning to Europe with a new concept of nature that still shapes our thinking. He came up with the idea that nature is a web of life and that earth is a living organism. He even predicted harmful human–induced climate change and warned about the devastating environmental effects of monoculture, irrigation, deforestation and industrial pollution.</p> <p>Having read his letters and diaries, I was determined to travel to the Andes, where he had spent several months, and to the Orinoco where he had been stunned by the rich life in the rainforest. I was lucky, because in 2013 I was the Eccles British Library writer-in-residence, a generous award that allowed me to follow Humboldt’s footsteps through South America. It was as exhilarating as it was hard. At the Orinoco in Venezuela, I encountered (too many) tarantulas, but I also observed river dolphins and listened to the bellowing cries of howler monkeys at night. In the Andes, I was trying to experience what Humboldt must have felt but there was absolutely no way that I was going to hang over a precarious small ledge on Pichincha to stare in the crater of the volcano as he had done. At 13,000 feet on Antisana volcano in Ecuador, I was thrilled to find the hut in which Humboldt had spent a miserable night in 1802. At that very moment, a herd of wild horses surrounded me and four majestic condors circled above – a pretty good day’s research! </p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"2389f3285099215511de3ccbfd227bc131006f2e\"> <img src=\"https://media.guim.co.uk/2389f3285099215511de3ccbfd227bc131006f2e/0_154_2048_1229/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Andrea Wulf on top of Antisana volcano in Ecuador\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Andrea Wulf on top of Antisana volcano in Ecuador.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Julia-Niharika Sen</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>But the most exciting moment for me was climbing Chimborazo, a mountain that had been foundational in Humboldt’s vision of nature. I made it only to 16,400ft – it rises to more than 20,000 – but my admiration for his endurance and achievements grew with every heavy step. The clouds rolled in below me, but I was bathed in sunshine. It felt like standing on the top of the world (and somehow next to Humboldt). </p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--supporting\" data-media-id=\"223c79ed2e89bfd3397f81be923d20975569ed76\"> <img src=\"https://media.guim.co.uk/223c79ed2e89bfd3397f81be923d20975569ed76/0_134_3872_2324/1000.jpg\" alt=\"A Humboldt penguin (Spheniscus humboldti) swimming under blue water.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">A Humboldt penguin (Spheniscus humboldti) swimming under blue water.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Alamy</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>In many ways, The Invention of Nature continues to be a journey. For the past few years, whenever I told people that I was writing a book about Alexander von Humboldt, the most common response was a blank face. Today, he’s almost forgotten in the English–speaking world, but his name lingers everywhere – from the ocean current that hugs the west coast of South America to a penguin, dozens of mountains, plants, rivers and a glacier in Greenland. There are more places, plants and animals named after him than anyone else.</p> <p>I’m determined to restore Humboldt to the pedestal in the temple of nature and science where he rightfully belongs. He’s the founding father of environmentalism and his approach to the natural world is still immensely relevant. He was an interdisciplinary scientist who brought the arts and sciences together. </p> <p>Humboldt believed that we can only understand nature by using our imagination. He was driven by a sense of wonder for nature that I believe is missing in today’s political debates about climate change. When I give talks or interviews, I don’t feel that I’m promoting my book, but that I’m doing publicity for him.</p> <p>When the book was published last year, I was worried that no one would buy a biography about a man they had never heard of – but they did. <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/jan/04/kate-atkinson-wins-costa-novel-prize-for-a-god-in-ruins\">It even won the Costa biography prize</a>. I just returned from a 34–talk US book tour and every single time I go on stage to talk about Humboldt, I’m excited to see how people respond to him. Young readers, environmentalists, conservationists or people who are usually not interested in history tell me how amazed they are about this man. That is a part of my journey that makes my heart skip every day.</p> <h2>Extract</h2> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>They were crawling on hands and knees along a high narrow ridge that was in places only two inches wide. The path, if you could call it that, was layered with sand and loose stones that shifted whenever touched. Down to the left was a steep cliff encrusted with ice that glinted when the sun broke through the thick clouds. The view to the right, with a 1,000-foot drop, wasn’t much better. Here the dark, almost perpendicular walls were covered with rocks that protruded like knife blades.</p> <p>Alexander von Humboldt and his three companions moved in single file, slowly inching forward. Without proper equipment or appropriate clothes, this was a dangerous climb. The icy wind had numbed their hands and feet, melted snow had soaked their thin shoes and ice crys­tals clung to their hair and beards. At 17,000 feet above sea level, they struggled to breathe in the thin air. As they proceeded, the jagged rocks shredded the soles of their shoes, and their feet began to bleed.</p> </blockquote> <h2>More about the book</h2> <p>Wulf imbues Humboldt’s adventures there with something of the spirit of Tintin, relishing the jungles, mountians and dangerous animals at every turn … [She] has an unfailing ability to spot an interesting quotation or a curious situation. She is very good on the cities where Humboldt lived and the rival atmospheres of Paris and Berlin … a superior celebration of an adorable figure. - <strong>Simon Winder</strong></p> <p><a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/nov/13/the-invention-of-nature-the-adventures-of-alexander-von-humboldt-andrea-wulf-review\">Read the full review.</a></p> <h2>Buy the book</h2> <p>The Invention of Nature is published by John Murray at £9.99 and <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/404858/s/the-invention-of-nature/\">is available from the Guardian Bookshop for £6.99</a>.</p>","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4kg2e","wordcount":"1050","thumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/bf2657326b5175b0c1e999e6e4a83e8ebb2032d5/52_636_2448_1468/500.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-06-13T23:00:00Z","standfirst":"<p>The author explains how her Costa-winning study of Alexander von Humboldt took her from libraries to mountaintops in South America</p>"},"webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/jun/07/andrea-wulf-a-journey-through-thousands-of-books-and-spectacular-landscapes","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books/2016/jun/07/andrea-wulf-a-journey-through-thousands-of-books-and-spectacular-landscapes","sectionName":"Books","section":{"id":"books","webTitle":"Books","editions":[{"id":"books","webTitle":"Books","code":"default","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books"}],"webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books"},"elements":[{"id":"bf2657326b5175b0c1e999e6e4a83e8ebb2032d5","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"https://media.guim.co.uk/bf2657326b5175b0c1e999e6e4a83e8ebb2032d5/52_636_2448_1468/2000.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/bf2657326b5175b0c1e999e6e4a83e8ebb2032d5","suppliersReference":"2086924","altText":"A portrait of Alexander von Humboldt by Friedrich Georg Weitsch, c1806.","ca